              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Managing Git issues**\n\nI'm dealing with a push rejection right now. I need to pull with rebase and handle any conflicts that arise. It’s crucial to check for untracked files, as the remote may have files with the same names, which could create conflicts. I’ll inspect the situation because if there are remote commits that include those untracked files, a pull could cause issues. I need to fetch the remote changes, compare them, and proceed with caution to preserve my untracked files."
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Handling potential conflicts in Git**\n\nIf the remote includes the same untracked files, I could run into a conflict where my local untracked files might be overwritten during rebase. The user mentioned not to delete or overwrite these files, so stashing them could lead to complications. I should inspect the differences in the remote first, as using `git fetch` won't impact my working tree. Once I do that, I can get a list of changed file names to see what's going on. This careful approach might be the best path forward!"
            }
          ]
        }
