            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Clarifying backup strategy**\n\nI’m thinking about how to handle backups that should stay outside the repository. The user asked to keep certain fremde untracked files unchanged, but since they’re already tracked remotely, updating to origin will affect that. I want to focus on the specific Palworld article, even though pulling in remote changes could complicate things with previous articles made by others. However, our commit won’t stage those extra changes, which is a relief!"
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Evaluating code conflict resolution**\n\nIt looks like we have a duplicate conflict with the origin's Palworld article, so I'll need to review that and integrate our quality requests. It seems the remote commit, possibly from the Content Factory, includes changes to the Palworld article too. I should check the path in origin to figure out whether to modify or replace the existing article. Also, I'll need to be careful about rebasing to avoid overriding the new index design from the remote. Let’s inspect the current state of origin."
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Resolving rebase strategy**\n\nI see that the origin already has the Palworld card, so I shouldn't undo the remote design. My local commit seems to be based on an older version, which could cause a rebase conflict. My best approach might be to reset the local branch to origin/main and then reapply our article improvements. I need to ensure our untracked files are preserved before the reset because using `git reset --hard` could overwrite them. I should stash those untracked files first. Let's figure that out!"
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Considering stash and reset options**\n\nIf I stash the untracked files, using `git reset --hard origin/main` or a rebase should be safer. But when I apply the stash afterward, it could fail if the remote tracks the same files. I might decide to keep the stash as a backup instead of applying it, which shouldn’t violate anything since it just moves them out of the working tree. However, I need to compare contents first to avoid overwriting what the user wants to keep. It feels like stashing is a safer bet overall!"
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Exploring git worktrees**\n\nWhen I see \"untouched,\" it means not deleting or overwriting files in the commit, but they might still be tracked by the remote. If I stash without popping, those changes won't be in my working tree. Maybe using `git worktree` could help—creating a separate worktree at `/tmp/hostazar-sync` from `origin/main` means I can work without affecting untracked files in the original repo. Since the user gave a repo path, I'll create a new directory for this worktree. I'll consider how to handle branches too."
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Managing git branches**\n\nI can add a worktree even if there are untracked files, but I can't use the same branch if the main branch is checked out. So I’ll either detach or create a new branch from `origin/main` and then apply my changes. Since the user wants to push to main, I might commit on the temporary branch and push that to `HEAD:main`, avoiding interference with the main working tree. However, my local main already has a commit, so maybe I’ll need to realign later without affecting untracked files. I should ensure the original main reflects the pushed state."
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Thinking through the git process**\n\nIt could be tricky dealing with untracked files that might collide, but maybe it’s not crucial. The user expects a final status for the repo path. I might use the worktree for the commit and push, leaving the original repo dirty and then reporting the status from the worktree. However, since the user mentioned the repo path, it might be okay if the worktree is linked. Still, it might be better to clean up the original repo afterward, considering the potential for collisions with untracked files."
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Considering article integration**\n\nI’m looking at how to integrate a new article based on previous commits. I see the current files and need to consider whether to copy content from the original. If I use a worktree detached at origin/main, I’ll need to inspect the remote Palworld to see if it meets the user’s request for a new article. I might have to compare it with our high-quality version and decide whether to overwrite or preserve some existing design elements. It’s a lot to weigh!"
            }
