              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Evaluating remote changes**\n\nI'm noticing that the remote doesn't have Palworld, even though it's listed in my HEAD. The difference indicates that the name could be due to removal from the origin. It looks like I need to rebase my commit onto the origin, but there's an issue with untracked files conflicting with the remote. Using a worktree might be a good idea to avoid moving those untracked files. I’ll create a fresh worktree, copy the article, and patch the current index. This way, the original untracked files stay untouched. I’ll consider how to handle the original branch after pushing."
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Addressing repo issues**\n\nI'm noticing the active repository has a dirty state with local commits that haven't been pushed and some untracked files. After a successful push from the worktree, I could reset the branch pointer to origin/main. However, changing the ref while checked out on the original branch could be risky. I could consider using `git reset`, but I want to avoid deleting anything since the user prefers not to overwrite files. Leaving the local main with duplicate commits seems problematic. Figuring this out will be easier after the push from the worktree, but I’ll need to think strategically to prevent future confusion."
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Handling original repository issues**\n\nI could manage the original repository better by first saving untracked differences into a tar backup. Then, using `git stash push -u` would stash all untracked foreign files. Once that's done, I can rebase the main branch onto origin/main and resolve any potential conflicts, particularly with the index or sitemap. Since the origin doesn’t have Palworld, the article addition should be fine. If there are conflicts, I’ll resolve them using the current origin index along with my additions, and then pop the stash afterward."
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Considering git worktree options**\n\nThe user specifically asked for the repository path, which needs to include the commit and push details. However, our local main branch has an unpushed commit from an earlier attempt, and that could be confusing. I should create a worktree from the original with `git rebase --autostash` to preserve any untracked changes. I'll also need to make sure no existing paths get overwritten. I think using the terminal for copying the article content to the worktree is the simplest approach!"
            },
            {
              "type": "summary_text",
              "text": "**Patching worktree index**\n\nNext, I need to patch the index or sitemap in the worktree. It’s important to inspect the origin index structure, specifically around the BlogPosting array and the blog grid. To do this effectively, I’ll use the `read_file` function from the worktree. There’s also a chance I might need to apply `search_files` to locate everything correctly. This way, I can make sure everything is aligned as needed for the user!"
            }
