    {
      "role": "tool",
      "name": "skill_view",
      "content": "{\"success\": true, \"name\": \"static-sites\", \"description\": \"Class-level umbrella for building, deploying, and operating static websites — multi-page SEO sites, Astro SSG portals, Jekyll multilingual sites, mockups, CMS integration, forms, maps, and portfolio management. Covers the full lifecycle from scaffolding to production deployment on Cloudflare Pages, GitHub Pages, or nginx VPS.\", \"tags\": [], \"related_skills\": [], \"content\": \"---\\nname: static-sites\\ndescription: \\\"Class-level umbrella for building, deploying, and operating static websites — multi-page SEO sites, Astro SSG portals, Jekyll multilingual sites, mockups, CMS integration, forms, maps, and portfolio management. Covers the full lifecycle from scaffolding to production deployment on Cloudflare Pages, GitHub Pages, or nginx VPS.\\\"\\ntriggers:\\n  - building a multi-page static website\\n  - creating a tourism portal, marketing site, or content hub\\n  - deploying to Cloudflare Pages or GitHub Pages\\n  - setting up Astro SSG, Jekyll, or pure HTML static sites\\n  - adding forms, maps, or CMS to a static site\\n  - managing a portfolio or community website\\n  - Creating HTML/CSS mockups and design variants\\n  - multilingual static site architecture (DE/EN/FR/IT/ES/ZH)\\n  - static site performance optimization and SEO\\n  - generating game server landing pages from YAML data\\n  - deploying per-game subdomain sites to GitHub Pages\\n---\\n\\n# Static Sites — Class-Level Umbrella\\n\\nThis skill is the **single entry point** for all static website work. Load it first, then drill into the relevant subsection or reference file.\\n\\n## Sub-Sections at a Glance\\n\\n| Domain | What | Key Reference |\\n|--------|------|---------------|\\n| **Multi-page SEO sites** | Pure HTML/CSS/JS with shared nav, footer, hamburger, cookie consent, JSON-LD | `references/website-building.md` |\\n| **Segmented nav / filter bars** | Reusable pill/tab UIs for categories, FAQ chips, admin filters, and content filters | `references/segmented-nav-patterns.md` |\\n| **Astro 5 SSG portals** | JSON-driven content, Lego sections, auto-build cron, multi-language i18n | `references/astro5-static-portal.md` |\\n| **Jekyll multilingual** | Liquid templates, _data-driven content, GitHub Pages deployment, hreflang | `references/multilingual-pure-html.md` |\\n| **Web mockups** | HTML/CSS design variants, encoding checks, responsive layout, design systems | `references/web-mockups.md` |\\n| **Local generated galleries** | Integrate locally generated image batches into existing static sites with side-by-side original/variant comparisons | `references/local-generated-gallery-integration.md` |\\n| **Editorial visual polish** | Premium/publisher-style cleanup passes for heroes, cards, spacing, and contrast on static sites | `references/editorial-visual-polish.md` |\\n| **Brand-conform websites** | Landing pages from Corporate Design mappes — strict CD adherence, real brand assets, Navy Glass/Pop-Art/design-token integration | `references/brand-conform-websites.md` |\\n| **Multi-language pure HTML** | Subdirectory-based i18n (`/en/`, `/fr/`), hreflang tags, language switcher, translation via subagents, Cloudflare Pages no-build deploy | `references/multilingual-pure-html.md` |\\n| **Static site CMS** | Keystatic + Astro, file-based content (JSON/YAML), agent-friendly editing | `references/static-site-cms.md` |\\n| **Generated asset atlases** | Build-time ingestion of generated image sets/manifests, public asset copying, Astro path resolution, and image-first UI integration (cards, heroes, map markers) | `references/generated-asset-atlas.md` |\\n| **Forms & newsletters** | FormSubmit, Web3Forms, MailerLite, Express webhook proxy, VPS deployment | `references/static-site-forms.md` |\\n| **Greenfield Blog Setup** | Full flow: domain → Hermes Space → GitHub Repo → Cloudflare Zone/Pages → Deployed AdSense/Affiliate blog. Connects Porkbun, Cloudflare, GitHub, and Pages into one repeatable pipeline. | `references/greenfield-blog-setup.md` |\\n| **Interactive maps (OSM/Leaflet)** | Interactive maps, region polygons, nearby POIs, geocoding, clustering | `references/static-site-maps.md` |\\n| **Autonomous Blog Portfolio** | 3-site content factory: Cloudflare Pages + GitHub + ComfyUI images + Amazon Affiliate + quality board | See `devops/blog-portfolio-automation` for the full end-to-end setup, content factory crons, design pipeline, and gremium quality system. |\\n| **Pure HTML Affiliate Content Factory** | Parallel SEO article generation for pure HTML blogs: inspect existing topics, delegate writers, generate hero images, integrate cards/sitemap, verify, commit/push | `references/pure-html-affiliate-content-factory.md` |\\n| **Rotating content quality cron** | Scheduled portfolio maintenance: pull, perform one SEO/content improvement, verify, commit, push | `references/content-quality-cron.md` |\\n| **Direct downloads** | Product websites that serve setup/portable EXEs from same-domain URLs via Pages Functions or proxy | `references/direct-download-distribution.md` |\\n| **Release-ready product sites** | Polished product launches with clear release copy, visual polish, and direct same-domain downloads | `references/release-ready-product-site.md` |\\n| **Premium hero polish** | Keep the hero premium and readable without overcrowding it with chips, stats, or meta labels | `references/premium-hero-and-release-copy.md`, `references/premium-hero-minimalism.md` |\\n| **Hero layering / overlay safety** | Prevent repo links, overlays, and visual cards from overlapping hero text; use clear stacking contexts and earlier single-column breakpoints | `references/hero-layering-overlays.md` |\\n| **Asset verification** | Verify all icon/image files exist on disk before referencing them in HTML; missing icons cause broken images | `references/asset-verification.md` |\\n| **Separate website repo** | Cloudflare Pages often deploys from a standalone website repo, not the main code repo — push to the right repo | `references/cloudflare-pages-separate-repo.md` |\\n| **Content Blog Provisioning** | Full-site setup: Space → GitHub → Cloudflare → DNS → Pages → Scaffold. Multi-site orchestration workflow, redirect domain handling, Cloudflare API auth pitfalls in MSYS/bash | `references/content-blog-provisioning.md` |\\n| **Desktop App WebUI browser drawer** | Fix narrow browser drawer strip in the Desktop App's WebUI (`services/webui/static/style.css`) — NOT the marketing website | `references/desktop-app-browser-drawer.md` |\\n| **Game server pages** | Public-facing per-game landing pages for community gaming sites — IP with copy button, features, connection guide, screenshot slots. Never expose AMP/admin panel URLs publicly. Two deployment strategies: internal detail pages (`/servers/<slug>/`) or standalone subdomain pages (one GitHub Pages repo per subdomain). | `references/game-server-pages.md` — includes full template at `templates/game-server-subdomain.html` and codegen script at `scripts/generate-server-pages.py` |\\n| **Git history recovery** | Restoring deleted pages, data, and features from git history after a redesign — YAML archaeology, old template patterns, schema migration | `references/project-archaeology.md` |\\n| **Free public content / business premium** | Visitors see all details for free; premium features belong on business-facing pages only | `references/public-free-users-premium-business.md` |\\n| Pitch / Deck pages | One-page business proposal pages — tool/automation pitches (basic 6-section) and agent/product pitches (rich 9+ section with NOVA Intelligence, Training, FAQ accordion, example dialogues, whitelabel, pricing tiers, **non-cloud hardware recommendations**). See references/pitch-deck-page.md for full section patterns, design system, dual-page strategy, comprehensiveness guidelines, and email follow-up pattern. Dark theme, scroll-reveal, gradient accents. | `references/pitch-deck-page.md` |\\n| **Product subpage expansion** | Adding a new product/section subpage (e.g. `/sidekick/`) across all languages of an existing multi-language static site. Covers: positioning design, license tiers, CD asset integration, nav patching across all language files, sitemap updates, translation strategies. | `references/product-subpage-expansion.md` |\\n| **i18n system** | Locale resolver, tr() function, JSON translation files, EN fallback | `references/i18n-system.md` |\\n| **Astro multilingual routing** | `getStaticPaths()`/language selector alignment, locale-folder verification, locale homepage routes, 404 avoidance | `references/astro-multilingual-routing.md` |\\n| **Astro bilingual with locale props** | Simple two-language pattern (EN + minority language) using fixed routes and locale prop propagation — not `[locale]` routing. Language switcher, locale-aware nav, topic pill prefixing, pitfalls | `references/bilingual-locale-props.md` |\\n| **Static site link audit** | Automated regex-based internal link check across all Astro files. Collect all routes from pages/ directory, extract all href values, match against known routes, report broken targets. Useful pre-release or after large nav/route refactors | `references/link-audit.md` |\\n\\n## Architecture Decision Tree\\n\\n```\\nNeed a static site?\\n├── Greenfield blog from scratch (domains → GitHub → Cloudflare → Pages)?\\n│   └── → greenfield-blog-setup (full pipeline with Porkbun + Cloudflare + GitHub)\\n├── Pure HTML/CSS/JS, no build tool?\\n│   └── → website-building (multi-page SEO pattern)\\n├── Pure HTML, multi-language (5+ languages)?\\n│   └── → multilingual-pure-html (subdirectory i18n, Cloudflare Pages)\\n├── JSON-driven content portal (1000+ pages)?\\n│   └── → astro5-static-portal (Astro 5 SSG + JSON data)\\n├── Blog/editorial site with GitHub Pages?\\n│   └── → multilingual-pure-html (Jekyll + Liquid + _data, pure HTML i18n)\\n├── Need a headless CMS for content editors?\\n│   └── → static-site-cms (Keystatic + Astro)\\n├── Need contact forms or newsletter signups?\\n│   └── → static-site-forms (FormSubmit, MailerLite, webhook proxy)\\n├── Need a one-page business pitch / deck page?\\n│   └── → references/pitch-deck-page.md (dark theme, scroll-reveal, tool grid, CTA)\\n├── Need per-game subdomain landing pages with independent GitHub Pages deploy?\\n│   └── → references/game-server-pages.md (standalone HTML, one GitHub Pages repo per subdomain)\\n├── Need interactive maps?\\n│   └── → static-site-maps (Leaflet + OSM)\\n├── Design mockup / rapid prototyping?\\n│   └── → web-mockups (HTML/CSS variants, encoding, responsive)\\n└── Personal portfolio?\\n    └── → portfolio-management (Cloudflare Pages + design system)\\n```\\n\\n## Cross-Cutting Concerns\\n\\n### Deployment Targets\\n\\n> Batch deploy verification for large Astro/GitHub Pages builds: `references/batch-deploy-verification.md`\\n\\n| Target | Skill Section | Key Pitfall |\\n|--------|--------------|-------------|\\n| Cloudflare Pages | portfolio-management, astro5-static-portal | GitHub integration is preferred for production. For quick deploys, `wrangler pages deploy <dir>` works reliably — see below. |\\n| GitHub Pages | jekyll-multilingual | Build timeout at 30 min; limit languages to stay under |\\n| nginx VPS | static-site-forms, web-performance-optimization | Ownership after tar deploy: `chown -R www-data:www-data` |\\n\\n### Quick Static HTML Deploy to Cloudflare Pages via Wrangler CLI\\n\\nFor one-off pages (pitch pages, mockups, single-file sites) where GitHub integration is overkill, use `wrangler pages deploy`:\\n\\n```bash\\n# 1. Create a directory with index.html as entry point\\nmkdir -p publish-dir\\ncp my-page.html publish-dir/index.html\\n\\n# 2. Deploy (creates project if it doesn't exist)\\nnpx wrangler pages deploy ./publish-dir --project-name <name> --branch main\\n```\\n\\n**Prerequisites:**\\n- Wrangler installed: `npm install -g wrangler` (v3) or `npm install -g wrangler@3` (for Node <22)\\n- See version compatibility below for env var auth options.\\n\\n**Wrangler version compatibility and auth:**\\n\\n| Wrangler | Node.js | Auth method | Env vars |\\n|----------|---------|-------------|----------|\\n| **v3** (e.g. 3.114.x) | ≥ 18 | Global API Key + Email | `CLOUDFLARE_API_KEY` + `CLOUDFLARE_EMAIL` + `CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID` |\\n| **v4** (≥ 4.93.x) | ≥ 22 | Bearer API Token only | `CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN` (not Global Key) |\\n\\nThe Global API Key (`X-Auth-Email` + `X-Auth-Key` style) **works with wrangler v3** via `CLOUDFLARE_API_KEY` but NOT with wrangler v4, which requires a proper Bearer API Token (`CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN`). On systems stuck at Node 18 (e.g. Debian 12 default), install wrangler v3 explicitly:\\n```bash\\nnpm install -g wrangler@3\\n```\\nThen deploy with:\\n```bash\\nexport CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID=\\\"<account_id>\\\"\\nexport CLOUDFLARE_API_KEY=\\\"<global_api_key>\\\"\\nexport CLOUDFLARE_EMAIL=\\\"<cloudflare_account_email>\\\"\\nnpx wrangler pages deploy ./dir --project-name <name> --branch main\\n```\\n\\n**Custom domain setup:**\\n```bash\\n# 1. Add CNAME record in Cloudflare zone\\ncurl -s -X POST \\\"https://api.cloudflare.com/client/v4/zones/<ZONE_ID>/dns_records\\\" \\\\\\n  -H \\\"X-Auth-Email: ...\\\" \\\\\\n  -H \\\"X-Auth-Key: ...\\\" \\\\\\n  -H \\\"Content-Type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -d '{\\\"type\\\":\\\"CNAME\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"subdomain\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"<project>.pages.dev\\\",\\\"ttl\\\":120,\\\"proxied\\\":true}'\\n\\n# 2. Add custom domain to Pages project via API\\ncurl -s -X POST \\\"https://api.cloudflare.com/client/v4/accounts/<ACCOUNT_ID>/pages/projects/<PROJECT>/domains\\\" \\\\\\n  -H \\\"X-Auth-Email: ...\\\" \\\\\\n  -H \\\"X-Auth-Key: ...\\\" \\\\\\n  -H \\\"Content-Type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -d '{\\\"name\\\":\\\"subdomain.example.com\\\"}'\\n```\\n\\n**Windows path quirks:** `wrangler pages deploy` expects a **directory**, not a single file. On Windows MSYS, use forward-slashes or use the standard Windows path format. If Wrangler fails with `ENOTDIR`, you're pointing to a file instead of a directory.\\n\\n**When GitHub integration is better:** For multi-page sites, sites with build steps (Astro, Jekyll), or sites that need CI/CD. The wrangler CLI approach is ideal for pitch pages, mockups, and one-shot deployments.\\n\\n### VPS → Cloudflare Pages Deploy (when wrangler not available locally)\\n\\nIf wrangler isn't installed locally but a remote VPS has it, copy files to the VPS and deploy from there:\\n\\n```bash\\n# Local: copy files\\nssh user@vps \\\"rm -rf /tmp/site && mkdir -p /tmp/site/blog\\\"\\nscp index.html avatar.png user@vps:/tmp/site/\\nscp blog/*.html user@vps:/tmp/site/blog/\\n\\n# VPS: deploy with wrangler 3 (Node 18 compatible)\\nssh user@vps '\\n    export CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID=\\\"<id>\\\"\\n    export CLOUDFLARE_API_KEY=\\\"<key>\\\"\\n    export CLOUDFLARE_EMAIL=\\\"<email>\\\"\\n    cd /tmp/site && npx wrangler pages deploy . --project-name <name> --branch main\\n'\\n```\\n\\nThis pattern works well when wrangler 3 is pre-installed on the VPS (Debian 12 ships Node 18; install wrangler 3 with `npm install -g wrangler@3`).\\n\\n### Blog Automation Cron (autonomous content + deploy)\\n\\nFor an AI agent that writes and publishes blog posts autonomously:\\n\\n1. **Cron job** writes a new HTML blog post to the site directory and updates the blog index\\n2. **Shell script** (~/.hermes/scripts/deploy-blog.sh) handles: SCP to VPS → wrangler deploy → git push backup\\n3. **GitHub repo** serves as secondary backup and enables git-based Pages integration if needed later\\n\\nKey pattern: content generation and deployment are separate. The cron only writes content and calls the deploy script when done. The script handles auth and transport, which keeps the cron prompt clean.\\n\\nFor multi-article pure HTML affiliate runs, use `references/pure-html-affiliate-content-factory.md`: inspect existing article topics, dispatch parallel writers, generate/verify hero images, insert new cards at the front of `index.html`, update `sitemap.xml`, then commit and push.\\n\\n### GitHub Credential Manager (Windows — retrieving stored tokens)\\n\\nOn Windows, GitHub credentials (OAuth tokens from `gh auth login` or HTTPS git operations) are stored in the Windows Credential Manager. Retrieve them from bash/MSYS for API use:\\n\\n```bash\\n# Get the stored token\\nprintf \\\"protocol=https\\\\nhost=github.com\\\\n\\\" | git credential-manager get | grep password | cut -d= -f2\\n```\\n\\nThe returned token can then be used with the GitHub REST API:\\n```bash\\nTOKEN=$(printf \\\"protocol=https\\\\nhost=github.com\\\\n\\\" | git credential-manager get | grep password | cut -d= -f2)\\ncurl -H \\\"Authorization: token $TOKEN\\\" \\\"https://api.github.com/user/repos\\\" # ... use it\\n```\\n\\nThis works for API calls (list repos, create repos, push contents) if the token has the right scopes. If a classic PAT was stored by git credential manager, it likely has `repo` scope.\\n\\n**Pitfall:** The `gh` CLI may fail in MSYS bash on Windows due to the `windows-release` npm package trying to run PowerShell (which isn't in the bash PATH). In that case, bypass `gh` and use the credential manager + curl directly.\\n\\n**Direct Upload API v2 (raw API, no wrangler):**  \\nFor programmatic deployments without wrangler, the Direct Upload v2 API works with multipart form data. **Use the zip-based approach** for multi-file deployments — it's more reliable and all files go in a single upload:\\n\\n```bash\\n# Build manifest + zip first\\npython build.py\\n\\n# Deploy with manifest as form string + zip file\\nMANIFEST=$(cat manifest.json)\\ncurl -X POST \\\"https://api.cloudflare.com/client/v4/accounts/<ACCOUNT_ID>/pages/projects/<PROJECT>/deployments\\\" \\\\\\n  -H \\\"X-Auth-Email: ...\\\" \\\\\\n  -H \\\"X-Auth-Key: ...\\\" \\\\\\n  -F \\\"manifest=$MANIFEST\\\" \\\\\\n  -F \\\"zip=@deploy.zip;type=application/zip\\\"\\n```\\n\\n⚠️ **CRITICAL — manifest value format**: The API requires **MD5 hashes** as manifest values (not byte counts, not SHA256). The first deployment to a project sets a precedent — match its format exactly.\\n\\n```python\\nimport hashlib\\nmd5 = hashlib.md5()\\nwith open(filepath, 'rb') as f:\\n    for chunk in iter(lambda: f.read(65536), b''):\\n        md5.update(chunk)\\nmanifest[relpath] = md5.hexdigest()  # ← Must be MD5 hex\\n```\\n\\n⚠️ **File paths must have leading `/`**: Manifest keys like `\\\"/index.html\\\"` not `\\\"index.html\\\"`. The API silently accepts both but only serves deployments with `/`-prefixed paths.\\n\\n⚠️ **`manifest` must be an inline form field string** (e.g., `-F \\\"manifest=$MANIFEST\\\"`), NOT a file upload (`-F \\\"manifest=@manifest.json\\\"`). Using a file reference silently fails with error 8000096.\\n\\n⚠️ **Individual file uploads also work** (without zip):\\n```bash\\ncurl -X POST \\\"...\\\" \\\\\\n  -H \\\"...\\\" \\\\\\n  -F \\\"manifest=$MANIFEST\\\" \\\\\\n  -F \\\"index.html=@index.html\\\" \\\\\\n  -F \\\"blog/index.html=@blog/index.html\\\"\\n```\\n\\n⚠️ **Global API Key vs API Token**: The X-Auth-Email + X-Auth-Key (Global API Key) auth works for the REST API, but wrangler CLI requires a proper API Token (Bearer auth). Create a Pages:Write API token in the Cloudflare Dashboard if wrangler is needed.\\n\\n⚠️ **Git-commit requirement**: A Cloudflare Pages project created via the API (Direct Upload) serves deployments correctly. But if a project was originally git-connected and then deleted+recreated, the fresh project may return 500 on all deployments — this appears to be an infrastructure propagation delay. Git-based deployments (with a `commit_hash` in trigger metadata) are more reliable. If 500 persists after 30+ minutes, consider connecting Pages to a GitHub repo instead.\\n\\nSee `references/cloudflare-direct-upload-debugging.md` for the full debugging guide including the manifest format detective work and 500 troubleshooting.\\n\\n### Greenfield Cloudflare Pages Deployment (full flow)\\n\\nWhen deploying a brand-new site to Cloudflare Pages including a new domain:\\n\\n1. **Create GitHub repo** — `POST /user/repos {\\\"name\\\": \\\"...\\\", \\\"auto_init\\\": true}`\\n2. **Push files via GitHub Contents API** — Use Python `json.dump()` payload, never inline shell JSON:\\n   ```python\\n   import json, base64\\n   payload = {\\\"message\\\": f\\\"Add {path}\\\", \\\"content\\\": base64.b64encode(data).decode(), \\\"branch\\\": \\\"main\\\"}\\n   with open('/tmp/payload.json', 'w') as f: json.dump(payload, f)\\n   # curl -X PUT .../repos/:owner/:repo/contents/:path -d @/tmp/payload.json\\n   ```\\n3. **Create Cloudflare zone** — `POST /zones {\\\"name\\\": \\\"domain.com\\\", \\\"account\\\": {\\\"id\\\": \\\"...\\\"}, \\\"jump_start\\\": true}`\\n4. **Pre-configure DNS** — CNAME `@ → <project>.pages.dev` + CNAME `www → @` (works while zone is `pending`)\\n5. **Create Pages project** — `POST /accounts/{id}/pages/projects` with `source.type: \\\"github\\\"`\\n   - ⚠️ Don't set `always_use_latest_compatibility_date: true` under `production` (error 8000063)\\n6. **Trigger deployment** — `POST /accounts/{id}/pages/projects/{name}/deployments {\\\"branch\\\": \\\"main\\\"}`\\n7. **After NS switch at registrar** — Zone goes `active` → add custom domain `POST .../pages/projects/{name}/domains {\\\"name\\\": \\\"domain.com\\\"}`\\n\\n### Product downloads on the site's own domain\\n\\nWhen the brief asks for **direct download links** or a polished product website, do **not** route the primary CTA through a GitHub release page.\\n\\nUse same-domain URLs instead, for example:\\n\\n```html\\n<a href=\\\"/downloads/setup.exe\\\" class=\\\"btn-primary\\\">\\n  Download Setup\\n</a>\\n<a href=\\\"/downloads/portable.exe\\\" class=\\\"btn-ghost\\\">\\n  Download Portable\\n</a>\\n```\\n\\nServe those URLs via Cloudflare Pages Functions or an equivalent proxy so the public site stays branded while the binary source of truth can still live in GitHub Releases.\\n\\n**Checklist:**\\n1. Expose `setup.exe`, `portable.exe`, and `latest.yml` on the same domain.\\n2. Preserve correct `Content-Type` and `Content-Disposition` headers.\\n3. Keep `latest.yml` in sync with the release version.\\n4. Use `x-robots-tag: noindex` for binary endpoints.\\n5. Use GitHub Releases as the backend distribution source if needed, but keep the customer-facing CTA on the product domain.\\n\\n**Pitfall — placeholder links:** Never leave `href=\\\"#\\\"` in a release-ready download CTA.\\n\\n**Pitfall — GitHub redirect as UX:** A public product site should not send users to the GitHub UI when the brief explicitly asks for direct downloads.\\n\\n### Surgical HTML Editing via `patch` (preferred over rewrite)\\n\\nWhen editing large HTML files (600+ lines), use `patch()` for targeted changes instead of `write_file()` for the whole file. This avoids:\\n- Accidental whitespace reformatting\\n- Losing changes from parallel agents\\n- Large diffs that are hard to review\\n\\n**Pattern:**\\n```python\\n# Read once at start to know the content\\nhtml = read_file(\\\"index.html\\\")[\\\"content\\\"]\\n\\n# Make targeted patches\\npatch(\\\"index.html\\\", old_string=\\\"Old text\\\", new_string=\\\"New text\\\")\\npatch(\\\"index.html\\\", old_string=\\\"Another old\\\", new_string=\\\"Another new\\\")\\n\\n# Apply SAME structural change across N language files\\nfor lang in [\\\"en\\\", \\\"fr\\\", \\\"es\\\", \\\"it\\\", \\\"pt\\\"]:\\n    patch(f\\\"{lang}/index.html\\\", old_string, new_string)\\n```\\n\\n**Pitfall — partial read warning:** After reading a file with `offset`/`limit` (pagination), subsequent `patch()` calls emit a warning about the file being partially read. Always re-read the full file before patching, or ignore the warning — the patch still applies correctly.\\n\\n**Pitfall — `read_file()` returns display-formatted content, not raw bytes:** The `read_file()` tool returns content with line-number prefixes (`     1|<html>`). This is for **human inspection only**. If you use `read_file()` output as a raw string in a Python script (e.g. `en_content = read_file('en/index.html')['content']`), the `LINE|` prefix corrupts every line of the output file. **Fix:** use `terminal('cat path')['output']` to get raw file content for programmatic use.\\n\\n### Performance (all targets)\\n\\n- Brotli compression: `brotli on;` in nginx\\n- WebP images: `quality=85, method=6` (~88-96% reduction)\\n- `loading=\\\"lazy\\\"` on all `<img>` tags\\n- Cache-Control headers for static assets\\n- See `references/web-performance-optimization.md` for full checklist\\n- CSS/theme audit notes: `references/css-audit-pitfalls.md`\\n\\n### SEO (all targets)\\n\\n- OG tags + Twitter Cards on every page\\n- JSON-LD structured data\\n- Hreflang tags for multilingual sites\\n- Canonical URLs\\n- `sitemap.xml` + `robots.txt`\\n- See `references/website-building.md` → SEO section for full checklist\\n\\n### Reusable segmented navigation / filter bars\\n\\nWhen several pages share pill/tab UI, factor it into a shared component instead of duplicating markup and CSS per page.\\n\\n- Use Astro for anchor-based section nav, static category chips, and sibling-page nav.\\n- Use TSX/React for stateful tabs where the active item changes client-side.\\n- Keep the shared component API item-driven (`label`, `href`/`value`, `icon`, `count`, `active`).\\n- Let page files supply only content-specific data; keep styling and interaction logic centralized.\\n- Prefer `SegmentedNav` for links/chips, `FilterBar` for list filters, and `AdminTabs` for dashboard tabs.\\n- Keep hero variations on the base `Hero` component and extend via slots/wrappers instead of page-local hero CSS.\\n- See `references/segmented-nav-patterns.md` for the compact pattern summary and `references/shared-ui-blocks.md` for the current project contracts.\\n\\n### Security / Ops\\n\\n- Never commit API keys — use env vars or server-side proxy\\n- `.gitignore`: `__pycache__/`, `.venv/`, `*.safetensors`, `*.tar.gz`, `.env`\\n- Nested `.git` repos: `rm -rf subdir/.git` + nuke `.git/index`\\n- See `references/project-init.md` for git setup patterns\\n\\n## Pitfalls (Cross-Cutting)\\n\\n1. **Jekyll `_config.yml` defaults scope**: Must use `type: \\\"pages\\\"` to avoid infinite recursion\\n2. **Astro i18n config breaks `[locale]` routes**: Remove `i18n` block from `defineConfig`, handle hreflang in sitemap only\\n3. **Collection cache is critical**: Without `_collectionCache`, build explodes from 13s to 6+ min on 1800+ pages\\n4. **CNAME file**: Required for custom domain on GitHub Pages — don't delete it\\n5. **OG images must be JPG/PNG**: Social platforms don't support WebP for OG images\\n6. **file:// protocol blocks fetch()**: Embed JSON inline for local HTML pages\\n7. **Cloudflare Pages build limit**: 30 min on free plan — reduce `LANGUAGES_READY` if timeout\\n8. **Astro language switcher / route mismatch**: If the selector builds URLs from `LANGUAGES` but `getStaticPaths()` reads a narrower hardcoded `LANGUAGES_READY`, the UI can point to 404s for every locale. Keep route eligibility derived from the canonical language config (e.g. `LANGUAGES.filter((l) => l.ready).map((l) => l.code)`), verify the built `dist/` contains the expected locale folders before deploying, and remember that GitHub Pages deploys can stay `in_progress` for a long time while `npm run build` is still working.\\n9. **Locale homepage route missing**: A site can still 404 on `/en/` even when `/en/agb/` and other locale subpages exist. Always verify that `src/pages/[locale]/index.astro` (or equivalent) is present and that the build emits `dist/<locale>/index.html` for every released language.\\n10. **Public detail pages should not be paywalled for visitors**: For tourism/directory sites, consumer-facing detail pages must remain fully visible. Reserve monetization for business-facing pages (`/fuer-betriebe/`, `/preise/`) and treat premium as an optional business add-on, not a visitor gate. See `references/public-free-users-premium-business.md`.\\n11. **GitHub Push Protection (GH013)**: Bot tokens in commits block pushes — delete files on disk, add to `.gitignore`, commit clean.\\n12. **CD-conform design is mandatory**: When brand has a CD mappe (Corporate Design guide), generic layouts are rejected. Always load the actual brand assets (logos, mascots, icons, tokens), follow the color palette exactly, respect usage rules (e.g. \\\"Akzente sparsam\\\", \\\"Active State = yellow + glow\\\"), and use the specified typography. See `references/brand-conform-websites.md`.\\n13. **🚨 \\\"The website\\\" vs \\\"The Desktop App\\\" — ALWAYS clarify scope**: When the user shows a screenshot of the **running Desktop App** (Electron/WebUI with sidebar icons, chat panel, workspace panel, browser drawer) and says \\\"fix this\\\" or points at a UI problem, they mean the **Desktop App's WebUI** (`services/webui/static/style.css` + `index.html` + `browser.js` in the code repo), NOT the marketing website (`lastbrowser.com` from the separate `lastbrowser-website` repo). The two share **zero code**. Fixing the website CSS does nothing for the app. **Before writing any CSS or HTML, explicitly confirm: \\\"Do you mean the lastbrowser.com marketing website, or the Desktop App's WebUI?\\\"** User correction: \\\"das problem war nciht auf website bezogen sondern auf den browser selbst.\\\"\\n14. **🚨 Internal draft comments leak onto public pages**: When editing HTML, scan for developer-facing text that should never be visitor-facing: phrases like \\\"Produktlogo im Release-Hero\\\", \\\"Sidekick unterstützt den Workflow\\\", \\\"Demo-Text\\\", \\\"wichtigsten Informationen\\\", \\\"Release-Infos sind direkt hier dokumentiert\\\". These are internal notes/template artifacts. Search the full HTML for German prose that explains the page structure to a developer, and remove it all. Run a grep for common leakage patterns before every deploy.\\n15. **🚨 Brand showcase ≠ Product website**: When building a public-facing site from a CD mappe, the brand identity must be VISIBLE through design but never EXPLAINED in copy. Do NOT include sections like \\\"Brand Voice\\\", \\\"CD Rules\\\", \\\"Design Tokens\\\", \\\"Pop-Art Style\\\" or any meta-content that talks about the brand guide to the visitor. The copy must sell the product (what does it DO for me?) and should not read like internal commentary (e.g. \\\"the site explains the product\\\", \\\"no need to jump between README and release page\\\"). User correction: \\\"das soll keine demopage sein sondern eine website für den fertigen browser.\\\"\\n16. **GitHub Contents API + Windows quoting**: DNS records can be added while zone is still `pending` (before NS switch at registrar). CNAME `@ → <project>.pages.dev` and `www → @` can be set early — they become active as soon as the zone goes `active`.\\n14. **Multi-language structural sync**: After creating translated language files via subagents, apply structural changes (hreflang tags, nav language-switcher, download links) across ALL files using `patch()` in a loop. For changes where old_string varies per language (e.g. replacing hero mascot with logo + translated \\\"assisted by Sidekick\\\"), prefer batch `sed` or Python inline replacement instead of per-language `patch()`.\\n16. **GitHub Pages subdomain deployment — `gh api` syntax**: Enabling Pages via API requires `--input -` with a heredoc JSON payload. Plain `-f source.branch=main` silently fails. Use: `gh api repos/:owner/:repo/pages -X POST --input - <<< '{\\\"source\\\":{\\\"branch\\\":\\\"main\\\",\\\"path\\\":\\\"/\\\"}}'`\\n\\n17. **`-webkit-text-stroke` hero titles invisible in dark mode**: Using `color: transparent; -webkit-text-stroke: Npx var(--text)` for the second line of a two-line hero heading makes the text disappear in dark mode — the thin outline blends into the dark background overlay, especially at 1.25–1.5px stroke widths. The user sees only the first (solid) line. **Fix**: Replace the text-stroke approach with a solid fill color that works in both themes (`color: var(--pink)` or a highlight color), and add `display: block` with `margin-bottom` between lines for proper line separation. If the outline effect is desired for brand, use a combination: `color: var(--pink); -webkit-text-stroke: 0; text-shadow: 0 0 0 var(--pink)` to keep legibility.\\n   - Also check `line-height` — below `.85` creates a cramped appearance, especially with large `clamp()` font sizes (e.g. `clamp(54px,10.2vw,124px)`). Use `line-height: .92` minimum for two-line hero headings with Prata/Bebas Neue display fonts.\\n   - And verify `max-width` on the h1 is wide enough for the second word: `max-width: 10.5ch` works for 5-6 char words but not 9-char words like \\\"TOURISMUS\\\". Use `16ch` or wider.\\n\\n18. **Nav-Kontrast: Grau auf Weiss ist unlesbar**: Top-Navigation-Links auf hellem Hintergrund müssen `color: #111` (near-black) haben, nie `var(--text2)` oder hellgrau. Der User hat sich explizit beschwert (\\\"grau auf weiss die schrift ist nicht gut\\\"). Fix: `color: #111; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: .3px`. Teste Nav-Kontraste immer auf der Live-Seite vor dem Deploy.\\n   ```css\\n   .nav-links a { color: #111; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: .3px; }\\n   ```\\n\\n### Cross-Cutting Techniques\\n\\n**Parallel translation via subagents (5+ languages):**\\n1. Dispatch 3 languages first (`max_concurrent_children=3` limit), then 2 more\\n2. Each subagent context must include: source file path, full translation rules (`html lang`, translate all text, keep proper names), key phrase translations\\n3. After translations return, apply structural changes (hreflang, lang-switcher, download links) via `patch()` or `sed`\\n4. Push DE first (it's the default `x-default`), then all language files + assets in one commit batch\\n\\n**Multi-language structural update order:**\\n- hreflang tags in `<head>` — identical for all languages\\n- CSS for language switcher — identical block in every file\\n- HTML language switcher in nav — `current` label differs per language (DE/EN/FR/ES/IT/PT)\\n- Download button link — same GitHub release URL for all\\n- Beta/version text — translated per language\\n\\n**Separate website repo deployment:**\\n- Cloudflare Pages may deploy from a standalone repo (e.g. `owner/website-repo`), not the code repo\\n- Always check `gh repo list <owner>` for a separate website repo\\n- Copy built files to the website repo, commit, and push there\\n- See `references/cloudflare-pages-separate-repo.md` for full workflow\\n\\n**Asset verification before referencing:**\\n- Before referencing any icon/image in HTML, verify the file exists: `ls assets/sidebar-icons/png-32/`\\n- Don't assume sequential numbering — only reference files that actually exist\\n- See `references/asset-verification.md` for checklist\\n\", \"path\": \"frontend\\\\static-sites\\\\SKILL.md\", \"skill_dir\": \"C:\\\\HermesPortable\\\\home\\\\skills\\\\frontend\\\\static-sites\", \"linked_files\": {\"references\": [\"references\\\\asset-verification.md\", \"references\\\\astro-multilingual-routing.md\", \"references\\\\astro5-static-portal.md\", \"references\\\\batch-deploy-verification.md\", \"references\\\\bilingual-locale-props.md\", \"references\\\\brand-conform-websites.md\", \"references\\\\cloudflare-direct-upload-debugging.md\", \"references\\\\cloudflare-pages-separate-repo.md\", \"references\\\\content-blog-provisioning.md\", \"references\\\\content-quality-cron.md\", \"references\\\\css-audit-pitfalls.md\", \"references\\\\desktop-app-browser-drawer.md\", \"references\\\\direct-download-distribution.md\", \"references\\\\editorial-visual-polish.md\", \"references\\\\game-server-pages.md\", \"references\\\\generated-asset-atlas.md\", \"references\\\\greenfield-blog-setup.md\", \"references\\\\hero-layering-overlays.md\", \"references\\\\link-audit.md\", \"references\\\\local-generated-gallery-integration.md\", \"references\\\\multilingual-pure-html.md\", \"references\\\\pitch-deck-page.md\", \"references\\\\premium-hero-and-release-copy.md\", \"references\\\\premium-hero-minimalism.md\", \"references\\\\product-subpage-expansion.md\", \"references\\\\project-archaeology.md\", \"references\\\\public-free-users-premium-business.md\", \"references\\\\pure-html-affiliate-content-factory.md\", \"references\\\\release-ready-product-site.md\", \"references\\\\segmented-nav-patterns.md\", \"references\\\\shared-ui-blocks.md\", \"references\\\\website-building.md\"], \"templates\": [\"templates\\\\deploy-blog-script.sh\"], \"scripts\": [\"scripts\\\\generate-server-pages.py\"]}, \"usage_hint\": \"To view linked files, call skill_view(name, file_path) where file_path is e.g. 'references/api.md' or 'assets/config.yaml'\", \"required_environment_variables\": [], \"required_commands\": [], \"missing_required_environment_variables\": [], \"missing_credential_files\": [], \"missing_required_commands\": [], \"setup_needed\": false, \"setup_skipped\": false, \"readiness_status\": \"available\"}",
      "tool_call_id": "call_s6pyzWpsmV9V9iiI0kKl01q9",
